  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Potential prison sentences:\n- Up to 20 years in federal prison per offense\n- Maximum sentences can increase for more complex cases\n- Sentences may be enhanced if connected to other criminal activities\n\n2. Financial penalties:\n- Substantial fines, often up to $500,000 or double the value of the laundered funds\n- Potential forfeitures of assets involved in the transactions\n\n3. Additional potential consequences:\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Deportation for non-citizens\n\nThe specific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Specific circumstances of the offense\n- Individual's criminal history\n- Whether the laundering involved other criminal enterprises\n\nThe primary federal statutes governing money laundering include:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal offenses)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\nProsecutors have discretion in charging and can pursue various legal strategies based on the specific case details.",
